This film is not trying to make a point that "it's okay to have an affair if you are unhappy and are on a road trip to Paris." Stop jumping to conclusions, because one, it's just the trailer. You do not know any other details other than that the main actress is uncertain of her happiness of her marriage, and that she is on a road trip with her husband's friendly French business partner. While it is simple to assume that she would have an affair, any film enthusiast or anyone with common sense would be able to know, based on what is presented, especially in a trailer, you do not have all the details of the entire film. Also, this film seems to be a romantic, light-hearted dramedy, with a certain whimsy slightly similar to "Midnight In Paris." So having a straight-forward affair as some of you in the comment section may think, would not really fit with the style of the film. And again, you do not know all the details of the film. What about Alec Baldwin's character? Is his character a completely moral individual? And of Diane Lane and Arnaud Viard, did you witness any sexual advances from either character in the trailer? Don't be so narrow-minded and quick to judge. The film, I believe, seems to try to capture the essence of platonic friendship and a time of companionship for Lane's character from Viard's, to help her through her presumed marital troubles, while experiencing the beauty and food of France. See that Lane's character is constantly concerned of rushing to Paris? She is disconnected from the act of experiencing all that France has to offer, only thinking of Paris. Toward the end of the trailer, she grows personally, indicated by her renewed sense of adventure, wanting to take a detour before going to Paris. I believe the entire film will be charming. The ending is obviously uncertain, but to really think that she will definitely be in an affair is rash and unbecoming of any film-goer and anyone with a decent heart. And if she does end up with Viard's character, it is not because of lust, but of a deep connection between the two of them that Lane and Baldwin's character no longer share. The ending will clearly be decided based on the progression and interaction of all the characters through the entire film. So again, don't be quick to judge, even from a trailer.

Uhh, no it doesn't work like that. Copyright is done by international conventions between countries, a copyright held by another signatory country is still valid whether or not it's on the market in your country.

If it's not available in your country then it's out of print and not even released in your country and therefore it can't be illegal to download a bootleg.  They can't force you to buy an all-region player and order it from another country. Me, I have an all-region player for precisly BS like this, release in one country & non-release in another, but not everyone has the extra cash to spare.

Hollywood recently has wound people up, and yes, the debate has since been won on paying people for their work - but who sowed the seeds for this in the first place, whose greed? I don't set the rules, and actually as a musician who has paid more to play than has been paid to play, so I know how it feels, thank-you.

Are there more equitable systems than capitalism? Sure. Did Transformers suck? Probably. These are red herrings. The question is: knowing that real people have worked on a project, & knowing that ticket/dvd sales are factored in to the success of the project, why would someone think it's ok to view/consume the work without paying for it?

Supply-and-demand, focusing on the demand aspect - meaning the value of labour or a product (in $ or £) is dictated precisely by whether 'someone thinks the end product is 'good''. I don't like this but it's the reality and we do no-one any favours by pretending otherwise - except those who benefit from cheap labour and exploiting it.

You're deluded. Supply and demand economics contradict you completely. The whole of capitalism is based upon exploitation, which is precisely this 'enjoying someone's work & not paying for it [not paying enough for it] that you speak of. Blaming people for reacting to being at the sharp end of capitalism, squeezed between high rents/prices and being exploited for their labour even more than, say, Ginger Baker's generation was. I think musicians and artists should be the first to be paid, but...

The value of labor by you or I isn't dependent on whether someone thinks the end product is "good".   Especially for a smaller film like the Baker project, box office take & dvd sales are significant parts of the budget, & each time a fee is *not* collected for viewing, the budget is impacted. It doesn't matter what the film is. Art is the result of labor, & people who produce it need to be paid for their work. Enjoying someone's work & not paying for it is unethical. End of story.

Transformers 2 is worth paying for is it? For example. Sure, I'm trying to pay my way - but the 'art' has to be worth a shit first. A lot that the traditional industry has been forcing down our necks isn't cool. So we're recovering from that. Hopefully the playing field will be more level and there'll be less sharks around in the business.

"For once" you're going to pay?  People work hard to produce films. Why on earth would you choose not to pay to enjoy the fruits of their labor?  Everyone who produces art has bills and obligations.  Don't steal.

I really like the Bobby Fischer story, and a few years back I was reading whatever I could find online about him. For those interested, the book "Frank Brady - Endgame" is a very good biography of Bobby, and Garbus' documentary "Bobby Fischer Against the World" is also a phenomenal account of his life.

Seeing this trailer, I could not help but notice the some over-exaggerated and fictitious stuff like:

- Bobby wearing paperbag mask (this is the first time I've heard about this 'situation') 
- Bobby yelling at Spassky at the beach (Bobby was always very gentlemanly towards Spassky, and that thing clearly never occurred)
- Spassky saying to Bobby "You don't look well Robert James" in the middle of a game (Spassky was the ultimate gentleman, and people rarely, if ever, exchange comments at the board)

Maybe these things happened and I just never managed to hear about them, but I am 99% sure they are just fictitious pieces created by the Hollywood nature of the production.

Also the casting choice was a bit strange. While Tobey Maguire (5'9"/175cm) looks a bit like Fischer, he is way shorter than Bobby was (6'2"/188cm). Also Liev Schreiber (6'3"/191cm) resembles Spassky, but he is way taller than Boris was (around 5'7"/170cm).

Anyway, I think I'll still watch this film, and hope to be entertained.

I hope they don't portray him as nothing but a maniac. He had some troubles, sure, but that's because he was a genius, and like all genius, they have a hard time dealing with the huge amount of stupid people doing stupid things in this world. The thing for example of not wanting people close when he played is not crazy, chess is a game that requires extreme levels of concentration, which is really hard to do when there is someone whispering or laughing around you.

Despite all of that, he was brilliant. He took on everyone and destroyed 99% of the competition and had absolutely nobody matching his genius at the time, not even Sparsky who is probably going to be shown in this movie like he was in the same level, HE WASN'T. Sparsky was really really good, but Bobby played what chess players like to call "beautifully". He was creative and extremely aggressive. Some chess players thought he played weird, but that's because they couldn't see what he saw.

At the age of 13 he sacrificed a queen to simply destroyed another player. Not impressed? He was 13 and the other player was a MOTHERFUCKING GRAND MASTER. Of course saying that he is the best player that ever lived is a little hard to prove, since the game has evolved beyond what he was capable to do at the time, but who is to say he couldn't keep up or develop more himself.

I'm pretty sure Magnus Carlsen looks at this and wishes he could play him, because he knows what a genius looks like, he is one himself, but he has never talked about Bobby like he was crazy, always talks about him as what he really is: a genius.

Madame Bovary isn't a 'classic love story'. It's a story about a woman who has a string of affairs because she's 'bored' with her husband, alienates all of her lovers (during which time she neglects and alienates her only child), accrues overwhelming debt, blames men for all her problems, and then commits suicide by eating arsenic, which, by the by, is probably the worst way to commit suicide because death by arsenic is painful, drawn out, and completely lacking in dignity. Seriously, I can't help but think that Flaubert was actually writing satire. If this is a great feminist work of literature, then feminism is in a sorry state.

In my personal opinion I never feel right with "True Event movies". To me it always feels kind of tasteless to dramatize real world events like this and it feels a bit wrong on the part of the audience to need a film based on a real event to get a reaction when we had many stories about mass murder in fictional contexts.

It may also be my personal preference. But I also think its a bit too early to have this kind of film made. Most times when a mass murderer or serial killer is made into a film its usually an older case with at least 20 years between the event and the dramatization of the events. Of coarse there are exceptions with true event cases like the amityville horror where the case is still fresh in the air while its being dramatized. But I don't know, maybe someone else could explain it better or contradict me. That is fine since I don't think there are right or wrong answers in whether to adapt a true event.

Do the morons who made this film not understand that this is exactly what the perpetrator of that massacre wanted? He wanted to become infamous that's why he chose a high profile film to piggyback of the popularity of in order to gain instant notoriety.

No one is interested in seeing the event from his perspective, no one cares how "depressed" or "lonely" he was as a justification for his act of violence. There's plenty of lonely, depressed people out there and none of them go out and shoot up a theatre full of innocent people. This guy was a psychopath/sociopath and that's all you need to know, he would have done something as abhorrent regardless of his social situation as he was an open and closed case of sociopathy.

If America was more concerned with focusing on the victims of these crimes as opposed to giving the perpetrators "celebrity status" then the situation wouldn't keep escalating.

 There have been a countless number of psychologists and psychiatrists who have made public statements advising the media to limit it's coverage of these mass shootings to only focus on the victims and not to mention or publicize the perpetrator, as the media coverage and notoriety is what the perpetrator was wanting to receive from the crime.

Making sociopaths/psychopath's "celebrities" is the worst thing you can do as it only encourages other sociopaths/psychopaths to follow in their footsteps and instigates them to also achieve that same level of infamy.

When normal people read about a massacre they are disgusted and upset by the event, when a sociopath/psychopath reads about a massacre they only acknowledge the amount of publicity the perpetrator has managed to achieve.

Profiting from a massacre is one of the most disgusting things another human being can do, especially when the massacre is so recent that surviving victims of that massacre can witness the "Hollywood version" of their traumatic experience.

I will admit I cried real tears. He's so far the only actor I've felt truly distressed over. Robin Williams is one of those actors where you didn't think about it, you didn't think he'd ever die, he was there in our childhoods, our teen years, and our adulthood. He's one of those actors where you smile just seeing him. Even in his worst work just seeing him made you smile a bit cause he seemed to enjoy doing what he did so much. And then you hear about the charity work he did, how much he wanted to help people, he just seemed to love making people happy. 

If I could turn back time it would be to give this man a hug. He seemed so happy, so full of life, its hard to believe and imagine seeing him in any other way. It goes to show that the way a person is, isn't all that they really are. But at the same time, how many of us wished we could have helped him you know? How many of us wished we knew so that we could tell him every day how much he meant to us as an actor. Its still just so heart breaking. And I'll be sure to see this movie so that I can see his final work.

I still remember the day he died...I was at home with my Mom, and she called me into another room and said, "Robin Williams is dead." And I looked at her and told her, "No, he didn't. You're lying. He isn't dead." I couldn't believe it. I refused to believe it. We had already lost so many celebrities that year, and I refused to believe that he would be another one of them. She continued, "They think it's suicide." I went into my bedroom, and that's where my dad found me about an hour later, sobbing.

The thing that helped me deal with his loss, as well as the other losses of 2014, was this: I don't think he would have wanted for us to be sad. And I'm always happy to see that other people love and appreciate his work. :')

I'm not sure I'll make it through the movie in one piece.  You hear about how people are affected by the death of famous people, but till Robin, I never entirely understood it.  Here I am though and his passing seems to have hit me harder than the passing of any family member (a short list that does include my birth mother, who I barely knew and a grandfather from my adopted family).  I still feel a sickening sort of feeling in my gut when I think about it and it still brings a bit of a tear to my eyes.  I'm still struggling to understand and to bring peace to that small section of my mind.  I can't help but wonder if like so many others, were the signs there?  Or was this really spontaneous like so much of his work?

I'll wrap this up with the idea that had his death been natural, no matter when, I think I could've dealt with it better.  Knowing the man I idolized felt his life should end by his own hands has weakened my foundation and I am still rebuilding.  I wonder if seeing this movie would help or if it would only do more damage.

 (1951) by J. D. Salinger comes from the poem's name. Holden Caulfield, 
the protagonist, misinterprets a part of this poem to mean "if a body 
catch a body" rather than "if a body meet a body." He keeps picturing 
children playing in a field of rye near the edge of a cliff, and him 
catching them when they start to fall off.
